**Course Prerequisite:** LIS 501 or consent of instructor.

## **Course Description and General Content:** 

A critical and interdisciplinary examination, incorporating human and social perspectives, of technology in the context of libraries and information organizations and of the complex relationships among technology, information, and society.

Course content includes digital media studies and critical theory, digital quantified self, data colonialism, artificial intelligence, surveillance, environmental media, digital labour, platform studies, library and archives content management systems.

## **Course Objectives:** 

After completing this course, students should be able to:

‚óè Understand, articulate, and critique the complex human, social, and sociotechnical  
contexts surrounding information and technology in libraries and learning  
institutions  
‚óè Become familiar with critical perspectives on information technology in libraries and  
learning environments  
‚óè Practice creating, evaluating, reviewing, and sharing knowledge to general and  
academic audiences  
‚óè Identify major trends in the design, adoption, and use of contemporary technology in  
libraries and information organizations  
‚óè Create digital media in a variety of formats to share knowledge with scholarly and  
general audiences  
‚óè Understand, critique, and apply research on the historical, social, political, economic,  
and cultural contexts of information to professional activities and practices in LIS.

## **Measurable Student Learning Outcomes**

‚óè After critical readings, lectures, and discussions in the technical, social, and cultural  
contexts surrounding libraries, information, and technology, students will articulate  
their understanding of these contexts through class discussions and written reports  
in these contexts.  
‚óè After critical readings, lectures, and discussions in the historical, political, and  
organizational factors shaping the relationships between technology, information,  
and society, students will demonstrate their understanding through the final web  
project aimed at an academic audience.  
‚óè Through written and media assignments, students will be able to practice digital  
literacy skills, and situate themselves in the socio-political context of knowledge  
production.  
‚óè Through written assignments and discussions, students will articulate an increased  
knowledge about issues related to critical information work in multiple contexts  
relating to library, archives, and information settings.

## **Program Learning Outcomes**

The course objectives and student learning outcomes above map to the following SLIS  
program-level learning outcomes (PLOs):

‚óè Evince complex and ethical awareness of issues, research, trends, and dilemmas in  
library and information studies.  
‚óè Demonstrate analytical capacities and problem-solving skills.  
‚óè Communicate effectively and professionally.  
‚óè Utilize and examine a broad range of LIS and cognate research and understand  
processes and methods required to conduct scholarship.  
‚óè Examine historical, established, and emerging impacts, importance, and limitations  
of technologies in personal, professional, and social contexts as well as in library  
and information studies settings.

### **Participation**

Participation consists of the following and will be evaluated on these factors:

1\. Contributing reading responses to discussion forums (throughout the term)  
2\. Completing your assigned role/tasks    
3\. Providing peer review and feedback  
4\. Creating, modifying, and editing content on Canvas.

*Peer Feedback*

Providing peer feedback is included in the course evaluation in order to prepare students for the realistic workplace setting. It is a valuable skill, which graduates of SLIS will be expected to give and receive on a regular basis in any professional environment. The expectation that our peers will be reviewing our work also raises the stakes for completing assignments in terms of their quality and thoughtfulness. Please use the Guide to Giving Constructive Feedback document, as linked in the ‚ÄúGeneral‚Äù section of Canvas.

*Class Discussion Forums*

The purpose of class discussion forums and participation is to have students engage with the readings, lecture and posts of others and to evince knowledge of the course materials. Discussion and participation result in students developing and demonstrating critical thinking and reflection skills. The discussion also allows students to connect the readings and lecture to LIS/library/information workplaces (broadly defined) contexts. There is **no requirement** for weekly discussion forum posts.

### **Policy on Late Assignments**

There is no penalty for late submission of assignments up to seven (7) days after the due date. Assignments submitted more than seven (7) days (including weekends) after the due date will not be accepted, and will receive a failing grade.

This policy applies to all assignments except participation (ie. completing your digital practice in Canvas is firmly due on Dec. 3 as the instructor is required to submit grades to the School/Faculty). Participation due dates are firm.

Unexpected downtime for cloud services, including Google Apps / Google Workspace at the University of Alberta, is not an accepted excuse for a late assignment submission. Exceptions to this policy will be rare and given at the instructor‚Äôs discretion. If you require an extension due to constraints, emergencies, and crises that will result in you submitting an assignment late or incomplete, please contact the instructor as soon as possible and in advance to make those arrangements.

### **Statements of Expectation for AI Use**

In this course, we commit to AI use guided by ethical and transparent principles. While students are allowed to use advanced automated tools (such as ChatGPT or Dall-E 2\) for certain written assignments, it is crucial to adhere to the following guidelines:

Seek prior approval from the instructor for AI use in specific assignments.

When allowed, clearly attribute and cite any AI-generated content in your work, including prompts and AI outputs as part of your academic record. Include an additional reflection component in your assessments, discussing how AI tools contributed to your learning process.

IMPORTANT: Please note that AI use is strictly prohibited in assessments and assignments not approved by the instructor. Failure to abide by this guideline may be considered an act of cheating and a violation as outlined in the relevant sections of University of Alberta (November 2022\) Code of Student Behaviour.

This assignment asks you to experiment with zine-making as a method of research-creation: a practice that integrates scholarship with creative production. The zine is not only an artistic artifact but also an intellectual intervention. You are being assessed both on how you mobilize ideas in a material form and on your ability to reflect critically on the process.

**Part I: Book Review**

As you build your review of the text, you will want to address the following:

**Purpose:** What was the aim of the book? What are the authors trying to accomplish? What is their argument?

**Audience:** Who was this book written for? Who is the author trying to convince?

**Approach:** How does the book attempt to achieve its aim? What strategies and evidence did you see in the book?

**Evaluation:** Is the book successful in accomplishing its aim?

The book review serves the academic scaffolding for the creative activity that follows in the zine making. It is the prep work to get the narrative arc for your zine in place.

**Part II: Zine Making**

Zines are a medium used to share ideas and information in creative ways within a particular community in a cost-effective way. Zines are quite often used to share non-hegemonic perspectives that are not particularly favoured by mainstream media outlets and publications, in this way, they serve to fill crucial knowledge gaps. You will want to consider the overall message of your zine, as well as the intended audience. When you write a paper it is intended for your instructor or professor only. Making a zine gives you an opportunity to consider another audience and purpose for your academic work, i.e. making your academic writing accessible to the layperson. 

**Instructions:** 

In producing your zine, you should focus your energies in the following areas:

**1\. Conceptual Clarity, Argument & Intellectual Stakes:** Your zine should have a central argument, theme, or question. It is not enough to assemble images and words; they must cohere around an intellectual purpose. The zine must say something. Whether through text, image, or juxtaposition, it should articulate a clear idea, intervention, or provocation that engages critically with your course materials or research interests. Ask: *What idea am I making tangible through this medium?*

**2\. Form‚ÄìContent Relationship:** The zine format allows for play, experimentation, and subversion. Attend carefully to how your design, layout, and material choices embody or challenge your ideas. Zines historically emerge from DIY and countercultural practices. Consider how the format, layout, and visual choices communicate your argument. Zines are not neutral containers; their design is part of their meaning. Think carefully about typography, sequencing, collage, and white space. If you are making a physical zine using materials, the physicality of your zine‚Äîpaper choice, folds, binding, hand-drawn or cut-and-paste elements‚Äîmatters. It should demonstrate intentionality, not haphazardness. Ask: *How does the way I present content change its meaning?*

**3\. Creativity & Experimentation:** You are encouraged to push boundaries. Consider collage, hand-drawn elements, found text, mixed media, or unconventional sequencing. The goal is not polish but inventiveness and thoughtful risk-taking.

**4\. Engagement with Audience:** A zine is meant to circulate. Imagine an audience for your work and craft with them in mind. A zine speaks *to* someone. Who is your imagined reader? How are you addressing them? Invest effort into how your zine invites, challenges, or disorients its audience. Consider tone, accessibility, and affective impact. Ask: *How will a reader encounter and respond to this?*

**5\. Critical Reflection, Process as Product:** Accompany your zine with a short written reflection (2‚Äì3 pages). Discuss your creative process, your intellectual aims, and what you discovered about knowledge-making through this medium. Reflect on your process: your intentions, design choices, and how the medium shaped your thinking. This reflection is essential to situating your zine as graduate-level work. 

Zines are meant to be creative works and as such are completely open to your artistic interpretation. This exercise is not about ‚Äúcraft perfection.‚Äù Rather, it is about using zine-making as a mode of inquiry. Zines allow for play, failure, and risk-taking. Invest your energies into clarity of thought, intentional design, and the courage to explore ideas in ways that conventional academic writing might not permit. Take risks, be inventive, and let the medium teach you something about the content. The strongest work will demonstrate an integration of critical thinking, creative experimentation, and reflective awareness.

**Evaluation Criteria:**

| Component | Excellent (A) | Strong (B) | Adequate (C) | Needs Work (D/F) |
| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |
| **Conceptual Clarity, Argument & Intellectual Stakes** (25%) | Clear, original, and intellectually rigorous concept; zine demonstrates a strong central argument or question. | Concept is clear and relevant, but stakes could be more sharply defined. | Concept is present but underdeveloped or generic. | Concept is weak, unclear, or absent. |
| **Form‚ÄìContent Relationship** (20%) | Formal choices (layout, design, materiality) are deliberately and insightfully tied to conceptual aims. | Formal choices support content but may lack depth or consistency. | Limited attention to the relationship between form and content. | No meaningful connection between form and content. |
| **Creativity & Experimentation** (20%) | Inventive, risk-taking, and resourceful; zine uses the medium to explore new expressive possibilities. | Creative choices evident, though somewhat conventional or uneven. | Some creativity, but largely safe or predictable. | Little to no evidence of creativity or experimentation. |
| **Engagement with Audience** (15%) | Demonstrates keen awareness of potential readers; compelling and accessible without oversimplifying. | Audience considered but not fully integrated into design/content. | Minimal attention to audience; work feels insular. | No evident consideration of audience or engagement. |
| **Critical Reflection, Process as Product** (20%) | Reflection is incisive, linking process, concept, and form to broader scholarly concerns. It demonstrates deep awareness of process, medium, and intellectual stakes. | Reflection is thoughtful but less integrated with the creative work. | Reflection is descriptive, with limited critical engagement. | Reflection is missing, superficial, or disconnected. |

For this assignment, you will critically engage with a scholarly book and present your review in the form of a podcast. Podcasts offer a unique way to communicate academic ideas in a conversational and engaging format.

This assignment asks you to experiment with podcasting as a research-creation practice. Think of the podcast not simply as an audio product, but as a scholarly intervention articulated through sound. You are expected to integrate rigorous intellectual content with careful attention to form, medium, and audience.

This assignment is meant to cultivate your ability to analyze scholarly material, synthesize complex arguments, and convey your insights to an academic and public audience through an audio medium. While you should maintain a scholarly tone, the podcast should also be accessible and engaging for listeners.

**Part 1: Book Review**

As you build your review of the text, you will want to address the following:

**Purpose:**

What was the aim of the book?

What are the authors trying to accomplish? 

What is their argument?

**Audience:**

Who was this book written for?

Who is the author trying to convince?

**Strategy/Approach:**

How does the book attempt to achieve its aim?

What strategies and evidence did you see in the book?

**Evaluation:**

Is the book successful in accomplishing its aim?

**Part 2: Podcasting Instructions**

Identify the most important aspects of your book review, such as the thesis or main arguments of the book, its methodology, key strengths, weaknesses, and your critical evaluation. Think of your target audience: Are they academics, students, or general listeners with an interest in the book‚Äôs subject? This will determine the depth of analysis and language used. Break your book review into segments. Unlike a written review, a podcast should flow conversationally. Outline these sections to guide the narrative. Podcast listeners expect a conversational tone rather than the formal structure of a written review. Simplify complex academic jargon where possible, and practice sounding natural and engaging in your speech.

In producing your podcast episode (10‚Äì15 minutes), invest your energies in the following areas:

1. **Conceptual Framing**

   * Your podcast should articulate a clear research question, theme, or argument. Treat the audio form as a vehicle for thinking through ideas.

   * Ask: *What is the central intellectual claim my podcast is making, and why does it matter?*

2. **Use of Sound as Medium**

   * Attend to the affordances of audio. Consider voice, tone, silence, pacing, and sound design (music, ambient sound, archival audio, etc.) as integral to your meaning-making.

   * Ask: *How does the sonic form itself shape knowledge production?*

3. **Structure & Narrative Flow**

   * Guide your listener. Introduce your theme, develop it through evidence or storytelling, and bring it to a meaningful conclusion. Balance accessibility with depth.

4. **Creativity & Experimentation**

   * Take risks in form, format, or style. Whether through interview, dialogue, sound collage, or experimental montage, your choices should serve your conceptual aims.

5. **Audience Awareness**

   * Imagine your listener as an interlocutor. Pitch your tone, vocabulary, and framing so that your ideas are rigorous yet engaging and comprehensible beyond a narrow academic circle.

6. **Critical Reflection**

   * Submit a brief written commentary (2‚Äì3 pages) explaining your process: your conceptual choices, formal strategies, and reflections on what podcasting as a medium enabled (or constrained) for scholarly communication.

### **üßë‚Äçü§ù‚Äçüßëüìë üì∫ Speculative Fiction Writing \- a.k.a. Black Mirror Writer's Room**

‚ÄúBlack Mirror‚Äù is a British science fiction Netflix anthology series set in the near future that explores the potentially dark consequences of technology and social media. Each episode has a different cast with a unique story, and, like most science fiction, it offers a speculative warning about what could happen if we lose control and allow technology to control us. This assignment is built upon [Casey Fiesler‚Äôs Black Mirror Writer‚Äôs Room](https://www.internetruleslab.com/black-mirror-writers-room) Assignment (2022). Speculative ethics activities in the classroom can encourage us to name, contend with, and address socio-technical hegemonies and the power and politics embedded in their worldly operations. As an analytic, such teaching and learning activities can further encourage us to center care-based responsibilities, accountabilities, principles, and practices when approaching, using, participating in, and developing digital environments for pedagogy and praxis. 

Here's Casey Fiesler's slide deck for your perusal: [https://tinyurl.com/blackmirrorwritersroom](https://tinyurl.com/blackmirrorwritersroom)

Ethics, particularly with respect to emerging technology, is so profoundly at its core about speculation ‚Äî because there are so many potential harms that are difficult to anticipate. They certainly manage to do that in the writers‚Äô room for the Netflix series Black Mirror, though. As an exercise towards this kind of ethical speculation, in this assignment, you will choose a social issue or technology (e.g. social media privacy, algorithmic bias, online harassment, misinformation, etc.) and then consider where it will be in five or ten years. What could be worthy of a Black Mirror episode? This exercise asks you to engage in speculative fiction not as escapism, but as a method of critical thought. You are being evaluated on the clarity of your conceptual intervention. Treat this as a space to test ideas, to risk, and to craft carefully.

A reason that Black Mirror is so compelling is that it often builds upon our existing anxieties about technology and pushes them just a step further. This is the perfect place to build from when using creative speculation to think through the possible consequences of new technology. Think about the episode of ‚ÄúBlack Mirror‚Äù that you have watched (Nosedive) or go on Netflix and watch one. Think about technology and social media in the near future. Read up on the future of technology by researching concepts and ideas that you have been exposed to in this class and developing it further by reading other articles on the subject. Read articles from popular news publications such as [Wired Magazine](https://www.wired.com/), [Smithsonian Magazine](https://www.smithsonianmag.com/), [Popular Science](https://www.popsci.com/), or similar source to come up with the idea for your episode of Black Mirror. 

For example, I have an idea for an episode where a young couple goes on a date to a very fancy restaurant. The fancy restaurant‚Äôs specialty is that it serves up an exquisite cuisine based on lab-grown human meat. I had read about [lab-grown meat on Wired Magazine.](https://www.wired.com/story/lab-grown-meat/) as well as about the art installation at the Philadelphia Museum of Art, titled ‚Äú[Ouroboros Steak.](https://designmuseum.org/exhibitions/beazley-designs-of-the-year/product/ouroboros-steak)‚Äù by Associate Professor of Fine Arts (Emerging Design Practices), University of Pennsylvania [Orkan Telhan](https://www.design.upenn.edu/fine-arts/graduate/people/orkan-telhan). I took those readings as my inspiration to come up with the story idea. And in my story, the couple at the fancy restaurant will encounter different menu descriptors that would use racial signifiers to semiotically convey to their clientele that they are indeed [eating the other](https://de.ryerson.ca/DE_courses/uploadedFiles/6052_Arts/CSOC202/Modules/Module_00/eating%20the%20other.pdf). You want to anchor your creative narrative in science and technology news articles that you have consumed, and these articles will serve as the inspiration for your episode. You are encouraged to tweak, remix, and racquet up a notch, a story that you read in a popular science and technology magazine and use your imagination to speculate on ethical quagmires that are likely based on the readings you have done in this class.

Feel free to talk to friends, family, colleagues and/or professors to flush out your ideas. Keep note of your ideation process in a journal; what was your process like coming up with the episode idea, and where did you draw inspiration from?  Consider the following steps:

1. Brainstorm near-future technology based on a topic of your choice. It should be close enough that it seems like a plausible future.  
2. What are the potential social implications and/or ethical issues and/or regulatory challenges with this technology?  
3. What do you think might be a cautionary tale related to this technology? Based upon the readings and the topics covered in the course. How do you see your Black Mirror episode telling a tale that conveys to the viewer the ethical and social consequences of what happens if the technology solutions were to develop in the ways that you have illustrated?   
4. What fictional person in the future could best illustrate this caution?  
5. What is their story?

Imagine that you‚Äôve just been hired as a writer for the television show ‚ÄúBlack Mirror.‚Äù It‚Äôs your job to come up with a storyline for your own episode. The storyline is the plot and premise of your episode, it is a detailed description of the story and the way in which the story develops over the course of the episode. Your episode will be featured in the next season of ‚ÄúBlack Mirror.‚Äù

Create a draft describing your episode and the characters that you imagine starring in it. What technology is used and how? Think about a scenario involving technology and social media, and take that idea to an extreme. There‚Äôs your story. Anchor the technologies that you are referencing to the readings that you have read in the course. Use a combination of creative writing and ethical speculation to consider what protagonist and plot would be best suited to showcase the potential negative consequences of this technology.

Please remember, the point of this exercise is not to produce a flawless short story, but to use speculative writing as a laboratory for ideas. Be ambitious\! Risk failure\! Writing that dares‚Äîconceptually and aesthetically‚Äîwill be rewarded.

**Grading Rubric:**

**Part 1 \[25%\]: World-Building as Argument**

Your speculative world should not be arbitrary; it must argue something. Construct settings, systems, and environments that make visible a social, cultural, or philosophical critique. What does this world illuminate about ours?

**Part 2 \[20%\]: Conceptual Provocation**

Speculation should trouble received categories, expose contradictions, or extend a possibility to its limits. Your piece should *pose a question* that lingers with the reader. Pose the question, What assumptions do I want my reader to re-examine?

**Part 3 \[15%\]: Characters as Carriers of Ideas**

Characters are not only individuals but vehicles for testing the logics of your speculative world. Invest them with perspective, agency, and conflict that reflects the conceptual stakes of your piece.

**Part 4 \[20%\]: Narrative Craft**

While you are invited to experiment, the writing itself must be legible and engaging. Narrative structure, pacing, and prose clarity matter. A reader should be oriented, even in an unfamiliar world.

**Part 5 \[20%\]: Critical Self-Reflection**

As graduate students in library and information sciences, you must be aware of the intellectual traditions you are drawing from or against. Your writing should show evidence‚Äîimplicit or explicit‚Äîthat you are thinking critically about genre conventions, histories of speculative writing, and your own positionality as an author.

### **üßçüìë üé∂ Critical Reflection \- Spotify Wrapped Unessay**

The Spotify Wrapped assignment takes inspiration from the Spotify Wrapped trend that pops up around the end of the year where everyone posts what their listening habits were like for the year. The popular campaign was established in 2016, and it combined Spotify user-listening data into an interactive display of the music the user listened to the most. Typically, Spotify Wrapped displays a listener's top songs, artists, genres and podcasts of the year and they were encouraged to share their Spotify Wrapped on social media. Here, you can take that same aesthetic and apply it to the course. In the form of a critical reflection assignment, where you creatively engage with all the concepts and ideas that you have come across in the course. 

This is an open-ended assignment where you get to construct your own critical reflection, having developed it from the critical thinking and analysis that you have done through the course of the term. In other words, what is the throughline that you see undergirding the materials in the course that has resonated with you? 

You‚Äôll be showcasing all the reflective work that you‚Äôll have done in your journaling activities through the course of the term in one snazzy creative output. You  are encouraged to mine your reading response journal to assemble this assignment with all the content that you engaged with rather seamlessly. You‚Äôll be operationalizing the reflective and journaling work that you‚Äôll have done through the course of the term, mining your reading response journal to assemble this summative output.

Questions, to consider:

* What are the critical concepts and ideas that you have engaged with in this course have stuck with you? How have you been thinking with the scholars you have read and engaged with in the course to help you think through the discourses of power and technology with respect to your own professional practice?  
* How have you thought about and thought through the pervasive and evolving relationship between data, technology, power, and human experience, often marked by a tension between control and resistance?  
* What do you find of interest studying how information systems are developed & deployed? In critically interrogating them for their profound impact on individuals and society, what did you find particularly intriguing?  
* There were several course readings that have built upon and cemented the idea that technology mediates power relations and how human beings actively engage in both shaping and challenging powerful, data-centric systems. Are there any exemplars from your personal and/or professional life that has animated these concepts and ideas for you?  
* As an information professional how do you think the intricate and evolving relationship between data, technology, power, and human experience intertwining with issues of power, surveillance, labour, and social justice impact your professional practice?   
* The course readings have tried to impress upon you the reader, that data-driven technologies are not merely tools but deeply impactful forces that shape our lives, demand critical examination, and require collective action to ensure equitable and just outcomes. What do you make of this premise, as it relates to praxis as information professionals and how does it inform pathways towards more just and equitable digital futures.  
* The concept of labour has been discussed throughout the course in the contexts of commercial content moderation, academic research, and Amazon's distribution centres. How do technological advancements transform the nature of work for information professionals working in the cultural heritage sector, namely, galleries, libraries, archives, and museums (GLAM) leading to issues like precarity, deskilling, emotional toll, and the commodification of human output, often obscured by narratives of convenience or progress?

Here's how Daniel O'Donnell defines the [unessay](https://people.uleth.ca/~daniel.odonnell/teaching/the-unessay): 

"The unessay works by throwing out all the rules you have learned about essay writing in the course of your primary, secondary, and post secondary education and asks you to focus instead solely on your intellectual interests and passions. In an unessay you choose your own topic, present it any way you please, and are evaluated on how compelling and effective you are." 

The main criterion is how well it all fits together. That is to say, how compelling and effective your work is.

An unessay is compelling when it shows some combination of the following:

it is as interesting as its topic and approach allows  
it is as complete as its topic and approach allows (it doesn‚Äôt leave the audience thinking that important points are being skipped over or ignored)  
it is truthful (any questions, evidence, conclusions, or arguments you raise are honestly and accurately presented)  
In terms of presentation, an unessay is effective when it shows some combination of these attributes:

it is readable/watchable/listenable (i.e. the production values are appropriately high and the audience is not distracted by avoidable lapses in presentation)  
it is appropriate (i.e. it uses a format and medium that suits its topic and approach)  
it is attractive (i.e. it is presented in a way that leads the audience to trust the author and his or her arguments, examples, and conclusions).
